\title{Cross-References and Citations in Web-Based LaTeX}
\author{Enhanced Pandoc-WASM Mathematical Playground}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction to Web-Based Cross-Referencing}
\label{sec:introduction}

This document demonstrates effective cross-referencing techniques for web-based LaTeX documents using Pandoc WASM. Since traditional BibTeX processing has limitations in web environments, this guide shows how to achieve professional academic formatting using LaTeX's built-in cross-reference system.

Key topics covered include mathematical cross-references in Section~\ref{sec:math}, manual bibliography management in Section~\ref{sec:bibliography}, and best practices in Section~\ref{sec:best-practices}.

\section{Mathematical Cross-References}
\label{sec:math}

Mathematical expressions can be effectively cross-referenced using the standard LaTeX \texttt{\textbackslash{}label\{\}} and \texttt{\textbackslash{}ref\{\}} system.

\subsection{Basic Equation Referencing}
\label{subsec:basic-equations}

Consider the fundamental differential equation:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:fundamental}
\frac{dy}{dx} + p(x)y = q(x)
\end{equation}

Equation~\ref{eq:fundamental} represents a first-order linear ordinary differential equation. The solution requires an integrating factor, given by:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:integrating-factor}
\mu(x) = e^{\int p(x) \, dx}
\end{equation}

Multiplying Equation~\ref{eq:fundamental} by the integrating factor from Equation~\ref{eq:integrating-factor} yields:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:integrated-form}
\frac{d}{dx}[\mu(x)y] = \mu(x)q(x)
\end{equation}

\subsection{Advanced Mathematical Expressions}
\label{subsec:advanced-math}

For systems of equations, we can reference individual components. Consider the matrix equation:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:matrix-system}
\mathbf{A}\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}
\end{equation}

The eigenvalue problem related to Equation~\ref{eq:matrix-system} is:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:eigenvalue}
\mathbf{A}\mathbf{v} = \lambda\mathbf{v}
\end{equation}

where $\lambda$ represents eigenvalues and $\mathbf{v}$ represents corresponding eigenvectors.

The characteristic polynomial for Equation~\ref{eq:eigenvalue} is:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:characteristic}
\det(\mathbf{A} - \lambda\mathbf{I}) = 0
\end{equation}

\subsection{Statistical and Probability Expressions}
\label{subsec:statistics}

The normal distribution probability density function is:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:normal-pdf}
f(x) = \frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^2}
\end{equation}

The central limit theorem relates to Equation~\ref{eq:normal-pdf} when sample sizes become large.

\section{Tables and Figures Cross-Referencing}
\label{sec:tables-figures}

Tables and figures can be referenced using the same label system.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Numerical solutions to Equation~\ref{eq:fundamental} for various initial conditions}
\label{tab:numerical-solutions}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
Initial Condition & $p(x)$ & $q(x)$ & Solution at $x=1$ \\
\hline
$y(0) = 1$ & $x$ & $1$ & $2.718$ \\
$y(0) = 2$ & $x^2$ & $2x$ & $4.389$ \\
$y(0) = 0.5$ & $\sin(x)$ & $\cos(x)$ & $1.459$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:numerical-solutions} shows numerical solutions to the differential equation from Section~\ref{subsec:basic-equations}, specifically Equation~\ref{eq:fundamental}.

